    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Equivalency of input parameters' factor in the ASME V&V 40 framework is specifically intended to address situations where the validation case uses surrogate or substitute input parameters that differ from the COU inputs — for example, when a scaled physical model, a different fluid, or a proxy geometry is used in experiments and a mapping argument is required to justify that the validation results transfer to the COU. In this assessment, no such substitution was made: the validation experiments were conducted on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry (CMM-verified, same manufacturing batch), using the same porcine blood analogue fluid whose properties were characterized and matched to the COU fluid specification, and at the exact 5 operating points that define the COU. Because the validation inputs are not surrogate or scaled versions of the COU inputs — they are the COU inputs — there is no equivalency mapping to establish or defend. Applying this factor would be a category error: it would require constructing a formal equivalency argument between two datasets that are, by design, identical in their input specification. This not-applicable determination is consistent with the ASME V&V 40 guidance that the factor is activated only when a deliberate departure from COU conditions is introduced in the validation activity. The assessment team reviewed this scoping decision in the peer review conducted on 2025-11-14 and confirmed that no input-parameter substitution was made at any stage of the validation campaign."
    }
